Step 1: Design and Test a Model Architecture¶

Design and implement a deep learning model that learns to recognize sequences of digits. Train the model using synthetic data generated by concatenating character images from notMNIST or MNIST. To produce a synthetic sequence of digits for testing, you can for example limit yourself to sequences up to five digits, and use five classifiers on top of your deep network. You would have to incorporate an additional ‘blank’ character to account for shorter number sequences.

There are various aspects to consider when thinking about this problem:

  • Your model can be derived from a deep neural net or a convolutional network.
  • You could experiment sharing or not the weights between the softmax classifiers.
  • You can also use a recurrent network in your deep neural net to replace the classification layers and directly emit the sequence of digits one-at-a-time.

Here is an example of a published baseline model on this problem. (video)

First, we'll download the dataset to our local machine. The data consists of characters rendered in a variety of fonts on a 28x28 image. The labels are limited to 'A' through 'J' (10 classes). The training set has about 500k and the testset 19000 labelled examples. Given these sizes, it should be possible to train models quickly on any machine.

In [2]:
url = 'http://yaroslavvb.com/upload/notMNIST/'

def maybe_download(filename, expected_bytes, force=False):
  """Download a file if not present, and make sure it's the right size."""
  if force or not os.path.exists(filename):
    filename, _ = urlretrieve(url + filename, filename)
  statinfo = os.stat(filename)
  if statinfo.st_size == expected_bytes:
    print('Found and verified', filename)
  else:
    raise Exception(
      'Failed to verify' + filename + '. Can you get to it with a browser?')
  return filename

train_filename = maybe_download('notMNIST_large.tar.gz', 247336696)
test_filename = maybe_download('notMNIST_small.tar.gz', 8458043)

num_classes = 10
np.random.seed(133)

def maybe_extract(filename, force=False):
  root = os.path.splitext(os.path.splitext(filename)[0])[0]  # remove .tar.gz
  if os.path.isdir(root) and not force:
    # You may override by setting force=True.
    print('%s already present - Skipping extraction of %s.' % (root, filename))
  else:
    print('Extracting data for %s. This may take a while. Please wait.' % root)
    tar = tarfile.open(filename)
    sys.stdout.flush()
    tar.extractall()
    tar.close()
  data_folders = [
    os.path.join(root, d) for d in sorted(os.listdir(root))
    if os.path.isdir(os.path.join(root, d))]
  if len(data_folders) != num_classes:
    raise Exception(
      'Expected %d folders, one per class. Found %d instead.' % (
        num_classes, len(data_folders)))
  print(data_folders)
  return data_folders
  
train_folders = maybe_extract(train_filename)
test_folders = maybe_extract(test_filename)

Now let's load the data in a more manageable format. Since, depending on your computer setup you might not be able to fit it all in memory, we'll load each class into a separate dataset, store them on disk and curate them independently. Later we'll merge them into a single dataset of manageable size.

We'll convert the entire dataset into a 3D array (image index, x, y) of floating point values, normalized to have approximately zero mean and standard deviation ~0.5 to make training easier down the road.

A few images might not be readable, we'll just skip them.

In [ ]:
image_size = 28  # Pixel width and height.
pixel_depth = 255.0  # Number of levels per pixel.

def load_letter(folder, min_num_images):
  """Load the data for a single letter label."""
  image_files = os.listdir(folder)
  dataset = np.ndarray(shape=(len(image_files), image_size, image_size),
                         dtype=np.float32)
  image_index = 0
  print(folder)
  for image in os.listdir(folder):
    image_file = os.path.join(folder, image)
    try:
      image_data = (ndimage.imread(image_file).astype(float) - 
                    pixel_depth / 2) / pixel_depth
      if image_data.shape != (image_size, image_size):
        raise Exception('Unexpected image shape: %s' % str(image_data.shape))
      dataset[image_index, :, :] = image_data
      image_index += 1
    except IOError as e:
      print('Could not read:', image_file, ':', e, '- it\'s ok, skipping.')
    
  num_images = image_index
  dataset = dataset[0:num_images, :, :]
  if num_images < min_num_images:
    raise Exception('Many fewer images than expected: %d < %d' %
                    (num_images, min_num_images))
    
  print('Full dataset tensor:', dataset.shape)
  print('Mean:', np.mean(dataset))
  print('Standard deviation:', np.std(dataset))
  return dataset
        
def maybe_pickle(data_folders, min_num_images_per_class, force=False):
  dataset_names = []
  for folder in data_folders:
    set_filename = folder + '.pickle'
    dataset_names.append(set_filename)
    if os.path.exists(set_filename) and not force:
      # You may override by setting force=True.
      print('%s already present - Skipping pickling.' % set_filename)
    else:
      print('Pickling %s.' % set_filename)
      dataset = load_letter(folder, min_num_images_per_class)
      try:
        with open(set_filename, 'wb') as f:
          pickle.dump(dataset, f, pickle.HIGHEST_PROTOCOL)
      except Exception as e:
        print('Unable to save data to', set_filename, ':', e)
  
  return dataset_names

train_datasets = maybe_pickle(train_folders, 45000)
test_datasets = maybe_pickle(test_folders, 18)

Merge and prune the training data as needed. Depending on your computer setup, you might not be able to fit it all in memory, and you can tune train_size as needed. The labels will be stored into a separate array of integers 0 through 9.

Also create a validation dataset for hyperparameter tuning.

In [ ]:
def make_arrays(nb_rows, img_size):
  if nb_rows:
    dataset = np.ndarray((nb_rows, img_size, img_size), dtype=np.float32)
    labels = np.ndarray(nb_rows, dtype=np.int32)
  else:
    dataset, labels = None, None
  return dataset, labels

def merge_datasets(pickle_files, train_size, valid_size=0):
  num_classes = len(pickle_files)
  valid_dataset, valid_labels = make_arrays(valid_size, image_size)
  train_dataset, train_labels = make_arrays(train_size, image_size)
  vsize_per_class = valid_size // num_classes
  tsize_per_class = train_size // num_classes
    
  start_v, start_t = 0, 0
  end_v, end_t = vsize_per_class, tsize_per_class
  end_l = vsize_per_class+tsize_per_class
  for label, pickle_file in enumerate(pickle_files):       
    try:
      with open(pickle_file, 'rb') as f:
        letter_set = pickle.load(f)
        # let's shuffle the letters to have random validation and training set
        np.random.shuffle(letter_set)
        if valid_dataset is not None:
          valid_letter = letter_set[:vsize_per_class, :, :]
          valid_dataset[start_v:end_v, :, :] = valid_letter
          valid_labels[start_v:end_v] = label
          start_v += vsize_per_class
          end_v += vsize_per_class
                    
        train_letter = letter_set[vsize_per_class:end_l, :, :]
        train_dataset[start_t:end_t, :, :] = train_letter
        train_labels[start_t:end_t] = label
        start_t += tsize_per_class
        end_t += tsize_per_class
    except Exception as e:
      print('Unable to process data from', pickle_file, ':', e)
      raise
    
  return valid_dataset, valid_labels, train_dataset, train_labels
            
            
train_size = 200000
valid_size = 10000
test_size = 10000

valid_dataset, valid_labels, train_dataset, train_labels = merge_datasets(
  train_datasets, train_size, valid_size)
_, _, test_dataset, test_labels = merge_datasets(test_datasets, test_size)

print('Training:', train_dataset.shape, train_labels.shape)
print('Validation:', valid_dataset.shape, valid_labels.shape)
print('Testing:', test_dataset.shape, test_labels.shape)

Next, we'll randomize the data. It's important to have the labels well shuffled for the training and test distributions to match.

In [ ]:
def randomize(dataset, labels):
  permutation = np.random.permutation(labels.shape[0])
  shuffled_dataset = dataset[permutation,:,:]
  shuffled_labels = labels[permutation]
  return shuffled_dataset, shuffled_labels
train_dataset, train_labels = randomize(train_dataset, train_labels)
test_dataset, test_labels = randomize(test_dataset, test_labels)
valid_dataset, valid_labels = randomize(valid_dataset, valid_labels)

Concatenate sequences of five digits.

In [4]:
image_size = 28

def concat(dataset, nb_rows):
    catset = np.ndarray(shape=(nb_rows, image_size, 5*image_size),
                         dtype=np.float32)
    for j in xrange(nb_rows):
        image = np.concatenate(dataset[5*j:5*(j+1),:,:], axis=1)
        
        catset[j,:,:] = image
        
        
    showDataImages(catset, 2)
    return catset 

train_catset = concat(train_dataset, 40000)
valid_catset = concat(valid_dataset, 2000)
test_catset = concat(test_dataset, 2000)
showDataImages(test_catset, 5)

#reverse concatenate to make independent digits
l_sequence = 5
image_size = 28

def rev_concat(catset):
    nb_rows = catset.shape[0]*l_sequence
    dataset = np.ndarray(shape=(nb_rows, image_size, image_size),
                         dtype=np.float32)        
        
    

    
    data = np.split(catset, l_sequence, axis=2)
    
    for j in xrange(nb_rows/l_sequence):        
        dataset[5*j:5*(j+1),:,:] = [data[i][j,:,:] for i in range(len(data))]
   
    showDataImages(dataset, 5)
    
    return dataset

train_dataset = rev_concat(train_catset)
valid_dataset = rev_concat(valid_catset)
test_dataset = rev_concat(test_catset)

#concatenate labels
def concat_lab(labels, nb_rows):
    catlab = np.ndarray(shape=(nb_rows), dtype=(np.int32, (5,)))
    for j in xrange(nb_rows):
        label = labels[5*j:5*(j+1)]
        
        catlab[j] = label
        
    
    return catlab


train_catlabels = concat_lab(train_labels, 40000)
valid_catlabels = concat_lab(valid_labels, 2000)
test_catlabels = concat_lab(test_labels, 2000)
print(test_catlabels[:1])

In [4]:
image_size = 28
num_labels = 10

def reformat(dataset, labels):
  dataset = dataset.reshape((-1, image_size * image_size)).astype(np.float32)
  # Map 2 to [0.0, 1.0, 0.0 ...], 3 to [0.0, 0.0, 1.0 ...]
  labels = (np.arange(num_labels) == labels[:,None]).astype(np.float32)
  return dataset, labels
train_dataset, train_labels = reformat(train_dataset, train_labels)
valid_dataset, valid_labels = reformat(valid_dataset, valid_labels)
test_dataset, test_labels = reformat(test_dataset, test_labels)
print('Training set', train_dataset.shape, train_labels.shape)
print('Validation set', valid_dataset.shape, valid_labels.shape)
print('Test set', test_dataset.shape, test_labels.shape)

In [5]:
def accuracy(predictions, labels):
  return (100.0 * np.sum(np.argmax(predictions, 1) == np.argmax(labels, 1))
          / predictions.shape[0])
def accuracy_seq(predictions, labels):
    a = 0
    s = predictions.shape[0]/5
    for i in range(s):
        a += ((np.sum(np.argmax(predictions[5*i:5*(i+1)], 1) == np.argmax(labels[5*i:5*(i+1)], 1)) >= 4.9))
    return 100.0 * a / s
In [6]:
# Network Parameters
n_hidden_1 = 1024 # 1st layer num features
n_hidden_2 = 512 # 2nd layer num features
n_input = 784 # MNIST data input (img shape: 28*28)
n_classes = 10 # MNIST total classes (0-9 digits)
batch_size = 100
p = 1e-5

graph = tf.Graph()
with graph.as_default():

    
    
    

    # tf Graph input
    tf_train_dataset = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, shape=(batch_size, n_input))
    tf_train_labels = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, shape=(batch_size, n_classes))
    tf_valid_dataset = tf.constant(valid_dataset)
    tf_test_dataset = tf.constant(test_dataset)

    # Create model
    def multilayer_perceptron(_X, _weights, _biases):
        layer_1 = tf.nn.relu(tf.add(tf.matmul(_X, _weights['h1']), _biases['b1'])) #Hidden layer with RELU activation
        layer_2 = tf.nn.relu(tf.add(tf.matmul(layer_1, _weights['h2']), _biases['b2'])) #Hidden layer with RELU activation
        return tf.matmul(layer_2, _weights['out']) + _biases['out']

    # Store layers weight & bias
    weights = {
        'h1': tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal([n_input, n_hidden_1], stddev = 0.05)),
        'h2': tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal([n_hidden_1, n_hidden_2], stddev = 0.05)),
        'out': tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal([n_hidden_2, n_classes], stddev = 0.05))
    }
    biases = {
        'b1': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([n_hidden_1])),
        'b2': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([n_hidden_2])),
        'out': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([n_classes]))
    }
    
    regularizer = np.multiply(p, tf.nn.l2_loss(weights['h1']))


    # Construct model
    pred = multilayer_perceptron(tf_train_dataset, weights, biases)

    # Define loss and optimizer
    loss = tf.reduce_mean(tf.nn.softmax_cross_entropy_with_logits(pred, tf_train_labels)) + regularizer# Softmax loss
    global_step = tf.Variable(0)  # count the number of steps taken.
    learning_rate = tf.train.exponential_decay(0.4, global_step, 1000, 0.65, staircase=True)
    optimizer = tf.train.GradientDescentOptimizer(learning_rate).minimize(loss, global_step=global_step)

     # Predictions for the training, validation, and test data.
  
    train_prediction = tf.nn.softmax(pred)
    valid_prediction = tf.nn.softmax(multilayer_perceptron (tf_valid_dataset, weights, biases))
    test_prediction = tf.nn.softmax(multilayer_perceptron(tf_test_dataset, weights, biases))
In [7]:
num_steps = 2001

with tf.Session(graph=graph) as session:
  tf.initialize_all_variables().run()
  print("Initialized")
  for step in range(num_steps):
    # Pick an offset within the training data, which has been randomized.
    # Note: we could use better randomization across epochs.
    offset = (step * batch_size) % (train_labels.shape[0])
    # Generate a minibatch.
    batch_data = train_dataset[offset:(offset + batch_size), :]
    batch_labels = train_labels[offset:(offset + batch_size), :]
    # Prepare a dictionary telling the session where to feed the minibatch.
    # The key of the dictionary is the placeholder node of the graph to be fed,
    # and the value is the numpy array to feed to it.
    feed_dict = {tf_train_dataset : batch_data, tf_train_labels : batch_labels}
    _, l, predictions = session.run(
      [optimizer, loss, train_prediction], feed_dict=feed_dict)
    if (step % 100 == 0):
      print("Minibatch loss at step %d: %f" % (step, l))
      print("Minibatch accuracy: %.1f%%" % accuracy(predictions, batch_labels))
      print("Validation accuracy: %.1f%%" % accuracy(
        valid_prediction.eval(), valid_labels))
  print("Test accuracy: %.1f%%" % accuracy(test_prediction.eval(), test_labels))
  print("Test accuracy_seq: %.1f%%" % accuracy_seq(test_prediction.eval(), test_labels))

Question 1¶

What approach did you take in coming up with a solution to this problem?

Answer: I started with a simple LSTM neural net which was an adaptation of https://github.com/aymericdamien/TensorFlow-Examples/ . I did not want to use a convolution net as described by the published baseline because my computer does not have a lot of memory, and the Deep Learning convnets seem to require that for good results. I concatenated sequences of five images from the notMIST dataset and then broke them apart before sending through the LSTM in batches of five so that the optimization and accuracy were done for the sequences of five. I adjusted various parameters, adding layers to the LSTM, changing the number of hidden layers, changing the batch size, and changing the learning rate. The learning rate was optimized at .001 and the batch size at 40. Changing the layers did not seem to affect the result. The accuracy for individual letters is good, ~.92 but requiring a perfect result for the 5 digits of a sequence to get a correct prediction is not as good, only ~.66. I then used my best model from the Deep Learning class, a relu perceptron with two hidden layers which improved the accuracy.

Question 2¶

What does your final architecture look like? (Type of model, layers, sizes, connectivity, etc.)

Answer:My final model has two hidden relus of sizes 1024 and 512 as well as an l2-loss regularizer and an optimizer with learning rate decay.

Question 3¶

How did you train your model? How did you generate your synthetic dataset? Include examples of images from the synthetic data you constructed.

Answer:I had 2000 training iterations with batches of 100 images from the concatenated sequences that were separated before sending through the neural net. I did not account for notMNIST images with bad labels that do not correspond to any letter which lowered my accuracy. The accuracy for individual letters is good, ~.94 but requiring a perfect result for the 5 digits of a sequence to get a correct prediction is not as good, only ~.75. The published baseline which achieves 96% accuracy on sequences had eight convolution hidden layers, far beyond the computing capacity of my PC. Below is a synthetic image: I would have difficulty identifying 2 of the letters below.

showDataImages(train_catset, 1)

Step 2: Train a Model on a Realistic Dataset¶

Once you have settled on a good architecture, you can train your model on real data. In particular, the Street View House Numbers (SVHN) dataset is a good large-scale dataset collected from house numbers in Google Street View. Training on this more challenging dataset, where the digits are not neatly lined-up and have various skews, fonts and colors, likely means you have to do some hyperparameter exploration to perform well.

url = 'http://ufldl.stanford.edu/housenumbers/'

extra_url = 'http://ufldl.stanford.edu/housenumbers/extra.tar.gz'

def maybe_download(filename, expected_bytes, force=False):
  """Download a file if not present, and make sure it's the right size."""
  if force or not os.path.exists(filename):
    filename, _ = urlretrieve(url + filename, filename)
  statinfo = os.stat(filename)
  if statinfo.st_size == expected_bytes:
    print('Found and verified', filename)
  else:
    raise Exception(
      'Failed to verify' + filename + '. Can you get to it with a browser?')
  return filename

test_filename = maybe_download('test.tar.gz', 276555967)

def maybe_extract(filename, force=False):
  root = os.path.splitext(os.path.splitext(filename)[0])[0]  # remove .tar.gz
  
  if os.path.isdir(root) and not force:
    # You may override by setting force=True.
    print('%s already present - Skipping extraction of %s.' % (root, filename))
  else:
    print('Extracting data for %s. This may take a while. Please wait.' % root)
    tar = tarfile.open(filename)
    sys.stdout.flush()
    tar.extractall()
    tar.close()
  data_files = [
    os.path.join(root, f) for f in os.listdir(root) 
   ]
  
  
  return data_files

def get_box_data(index, hdf5_data):
    """
    get `left, top, width, height` of each picture
    :param index:
    :param hdf5_data:
    :return:
    """
    meta_data = dict()
    meta_data['height'] = []
    meta_data['label'] = []
    meta_data['left'] = []
    meta_data['top'] = []
    meta_data['width'] = []
    

    def print_attrs(name, obj):
        vals = []
        
        if obj.shape[0] == 1:
            vals.append(obj[0][0])
        else:
            for k in range(obj.shape[0]):
                vals.append(int(hdf5_data[obj[k][0]][0][0]))
       
        meta_data[name] = vals
       

    box = hdf5_data['/digitStruct/bbox'][index]
    hdf5_data[box[0]].visititems(print_attrs)
    return meta_data

def get_name(index, hdf5_data):
    name = hdf5_data['/digitStruct/name']    
    return ''.join([chr(v[0]) for v in hdf5_data[name[index][0]].value])


print(get_name(22500, h5py_train))
print(get_box_data(22500, h5py_train))
print(get_name(0, h5py_test))
print(get_box_data(0, h5py_test))

def get_image_digits(index, hdf5_data, t):
    
    digits = []
    labels = []
    name = t + get_name(index, hdf5_data)
    box_data = get_box_data(index, hdf5_data)
    k = len(box_data['top']) 
    im = misc.imread(name, mode='P')
    for d in range(k):
        i, j = index + 1, d + 1
        s, t = str(i), str(j)
        n = s+'_'+t
        
        top = box_data['top'][d]
        height = box_data['height'][d]        
        left = box_data['left'][d]
        width = box_data['width'][d]
        label = box_data['label'][d]
        bottom = top + height
        right = left + width
        labels.append(label)
        crop_dig = im[top:bottom, left:right]
        #print(crop_dig.shape)
        shape = crop_dig.shape
        if shape[0]*shape[1]==0: zoom_dig = ''
        else: zoom_dig = ndimage.interpolation.zoom(crop_dig, [32./shape[0], 32./shape[1]])
        name1 = n+'.png'        
        if zoom_dig != '':misc.imsave(name1, zoom_dig)
        
        digits.append(name1)
    l = len(digits)    
    if len(digits) < 5:
        digits.extend(['']*(5-l))
        labels.extend(['']*(5-l))
    return digits, labels

image_size = 32  # Pixel width and height.
pixel_depth = 255.0  # Number of levels per pixel.

def make_dataset(hdf5_data, t, n):
    dataset = np.ndarray(shape=(n, 5, image_size, image_size),
                         dtype=np.float32)
    labels = np.ndarray(shape=(n, 5), dtype=np.int32)
    image_index = 0
    for index in range(n-1):
        digits, labels0 = get_image_digits(index, hdf5_data, t)
        for i in range(5):
            if labels0[i] == '':
                dataset[index, i, :,:] = 0
                labels[index, i] = 11
                
            else:
                
                try:
                  image_data = (ndimage.imread(digits[i]).astype(float) - 
                        pixel_depth / 2) / pixel_depth
                  if image_data.shape != (image_size, image_size):
                    raise Exception('Unexpected image shape: %s' % str(image_data.shape))
                  dataset[index, i, :, :] = image_data
                  labels[index, i] = labels0[i]
                  
                except IOError as e:
                  print('Could not read:', digits[i], ':', e, '- it\'s ok, skipping.')
                  dataset[index, i, :,:] = 0
                  labels[index, i] = 11
        
        filelist = [ f for f in os.listdir(".") if f.endswith(".png") ]
        
        for f in filelist:
            os.remove(f)
        image_index +=1     
    num_images = image_index
    dataset = dataset[0:num_images, :, :, :]
    labels = labels[0:num_images, :]
  
    print('Full dataset tensor:', dataset.shape)
    print('Mean:', np.mean(dataset))
    print('Standard deviation:', np.std(dataset))
    return dataset, labels

def showDataImages(dataset,n): # shows size of the sample    
    
   # indices=np.random.choice(dataset.shape[0], n)
    fig=plt.figure()           

    for i in range(n):
        for j in range(5):
            a=fig.add_subplot(n,5,(j+1))
            plt.imshow(dataset[i,j,:, :])
            # a.set_title(chr(labels[indices[i]]+ord('A')))
            a.axes.get_xaxis().set_visible(False)
            a.axes.get_yaxis().set_visible(False)
    plt.show()

  # Map 2 to [0.0, 1.0, 0.0 ...], 3 to [0.0, 0.0, 1.0 ...], 11 to [0.0, 0.0, ...]
    labels = (np.arange(1, num_labels) == labels[:,None]).astype(np.float32)

image_size = 32

def sharpen(dataset):
    rows = dataset.shape[0]
    datasharp = np.ndarray(shape=(rows, image_size, image_size),
                         dtype=np.float32)    
    for i in range(rows):
        image = dataset[i, :, :]
        datasharp[i, :, :] = ndimage.gaussian_filter(image, 1)
        
    return datasharp

train_digits_s = sharpen(train_digits)

In [5]:
def accuracy(predictions, labels):
  return (100.0 * np.sum(np.argmax(predictions, 1) == np.argmax(labels, 1))
          / predictions.shape[0])
def accuracy_seq(predictions, labels):
    a = 0
    s = predictions.shape[0]/5
    for i in range(s):
        a += ((np.sum(np.argmax(predictions[5*i:5*(i+1)], 1) == np.argmax(labels[5*i:5*(i+1)], 1)) >= 4.9))
    return 100.0 * a / s
In [6]:
# Network Parameters
n_hidden_1 = 1024 # 1st layer num features
n_hidden_2 = 512 # 2nd layer num features
n_input = 1024 # SVHN data input (img shape: 32*32)
n_classes = 11 # SVHN total classes (0-9 digits + blank)
batch_size = 40
test_batch = 6530
p = 1e-5


graph = tf.Graph()
with graph.as_default():

    
    
    

    # tf Graph input
    tf_train_digits = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, shape=(batch_size, n_input))
    tf_train_digit_labels_hot = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, shape=(batch_size, n_classes))
    #tf_valid_dataset = tf.constant(valid_dataset)
    tf_test_digits = tf.constant(test_digits)
    
    # Create model
    def multilayer_perceptron(_X, _weights, _biases):
        layer_1 = tf.nn.relu(tf.add(tf.matmul(_X, _weights['h1']), _biases['b1'])) #Hidden layer with RELU activation
        layer_2 = tf.nn.relu(tf.add(tf.matmul(layer_1, _weights['h2']), _biases['b2'])) #Hidden layer with RELU activation
        return tf.matmul(layer_2, _weights['out']) + _biases['out']

    # Store layers weight & bias
    weights = {
        'h1': tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal([n_input, n_hidden_1], stddev = 0.05)),
        'h2': tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal([n_hidden_1, n_hidden_2], stddev = 0.05)),
        'out': tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal([n_hidden_2, n_classes], stddev = 0.05))
    }
    biases = {
        'b1': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([n_hidden_1])),
        'b2': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([n_hidden_2])),
        'out': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([n_classes]))
    }
    
    regularizer = np.multiply(p, tf.nn.l2_loss(weights['h1']))


    # Construct model
    pred = multilayer_perceptron(tf_train_digits, weights, biases)

    # Define loss and optimizer
    loss = tf.reduce_mean(tf.nn.softmax_cross_entropy_with_logits(pred, tf_train_digit_labels_hot)) + regularizer# Softmax loss
    global_step = tf.Variable(0)  # count the number of steps taken.
    learning_rate = tf.train.exponential_decay(0.4, global_step, 1000, 0.65, staircase=True)
    optimizer = tf.train.GradientDescentOptimizer(learning_rate).minimize(loss, global_step=global_step)

     # Predictions for the training, validation, and test data.
  
    train_prediction = tf.nn.softmax(pred)
    #valid_prediction = tf.nn.softmax(multilayer_perceptron (tf_valid_dataset, weights, biases))
    
    test_prediction = tf.nn.softmax(multilayer_perceptron(tf_test_digits, weights, biases))
In [7]:
num_steps = 4001

with tf.Session(graph=graph) as session:
  tf.initialize_all_variables().run()
  print("Initialized")
  for step in range(num_steps):
    # Pick an offset within the training data, which has been randomized.
    # Note: we could use better randomization across epochs.
    offset = (step * batch_size) % (train_digit_labels_hot.shape[0])
    # Generate a minibatch.
    batch_data = train_digits[offset:(offset + batch_size), :]
    batch_labels = train_digit_labels_hot[offset:(offset + batch_size), :]
    # Prepare a dictionary telling the session where to feed the minibatch.
    # The key of the dictionary is the placeholder node of the graph to be fed,
    # and the value is the numpy array to feed to it.
    feed_dict = {tf_train_digits : batch_data, tf_train_digit_labels_hot : batch_labels}
    _, l, predictions = session.run(
      [optimizer, loss, train_prediction], feed_dict=feed_dict)
    if (step % 200 == 0):
      print("Minibatch loss at step %d: %f" % (step, l))
      print("Minibatch accuracy: %.1f%%" % accuracy(predictions, batch_labels))
  a = 0
  b = 0
  for i in range(10):
    offset = (step * test_batch) % (test_digit_labels_hot.shape[0])
    test_data = test_digits[offset:(offset + test_batch), :]
    test_labels = test_digit_labels_hot[offset:(offset + test_batch), :]
    a += accuracy(test_prediction.eval(feed_dict={tf_test_digits:test_data}), test_labels)
    b += accuracy_seq(test_prediction.eval(feed_dict={tf_test_digits:test_data}), test_labels)
  a = a/10
  b = b/10
  print("Test accuracy: %.1f%%" % a)
  print("Test accuracy_seq: %.1f%%" % b)

Question 4¶

Describe how you set up the training and testing data for your model. How does the model perform on a realistic dataset?

Answer:I used information from the bounding boxes to cut the images into individual digits. Then I rescaled all of the images to 32 by 32 pixels to run through the same models I used for the notMNIST data. On a larger test set than I previously had, my accuracy was ~.90 but the sequence accuracy was only 61%.

Question 5¶

What changes did you have to make, if any, to achieve "good" results? Were there any options you explored that made the results worse?

Answer: I tried a gaussian filter which looked better to me but did not improve results. The relu network performed better than the LSTM as with the notMNIST data. The parameter adjustment with batch size did not make a large difference for the relu. I had previously experimented with the learning rate for the Deep Learning course to optimize performance.

Question 6¶

What were your initial and final results with testing on a realistic dataset? Do you believe your model is doing a good enough job at classifying numbers correctly?

Answer:The LSTM only gave an 85% accuracy on individual digits and a 46% on full sequences. This was substantially improved with the relu as described in Question 4. I would need a large number of layers maybe in a convolution net to achieve the 96% accuracy on sequences of the published model. My model is not reliable, but I would need a more powerful computer to greatly improve the accuracy.

Step 3: Test a Model on Newly-Captured Images¶

Take several pictures of numbers that you find around you (at least five), and run them through your classifier on your computer to produce example results. Alternatively (optionally), you can try using OpenCV / SimpleCV / Pygame to capture live images from a webcam and run those through your classifier.

def showDataImages(dataset,m,n): # shows size of the sample    
    
   # indices=np.random.choice(dataset.shape[0], n)

        # a.set_title(chr(labels[indices[i]]+ord('A')))
        a.axes.get_xaxis().set_visible(False)
        a.axes.get_yaxis().set_visible(False)
    plt.show()

boxes = {}
image_size = 32  # Pixel width and height.
pixel_depth = 255.0  # Number of levels per pixel.


def get_boxes(boxes, image):
    if image not in boxes:
        boxes[image] = []
        imgray = cv2.imread(image, 0)
       # imgray = cv2.cvtColor(im,cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
        c = 0
        while c == 0:
            ret,thresh = cv2.threshold(imgray,100,255,0)
            im1, contours, hierarchy = cv2.findContours(thresh,cv2.RETR_TREE,cv2.CHAIN_APPROX_SIMPLE)
            #print (len(contours))
            if len(contours) < 2:
                c = 0
                imgray = (255 - imgray)
            else: c = 1
        for i in range(len(contours)):       
            x,y,w,h = cv2.boundingRect(contours[i])
           #print (x,y,w,h)
            boxes[image].append((x,y,w,h))
            #if i < 5: print(boxes[image[i]])
        boxes[image].sort()
    return boxes
    

def get_image_digits(boxes,image):
    
    digits = []
    
    box_data = boxes[image]
    k = len(boxes[image])
    #print (k)
    #print (box_data[0])
    im = misc.imread(image, mode='P')
   # print(im.shape)
    for d in range(k):
        j = d + 1
        t = str(j)
        n = image.replace('.JPG', '') +'_'+t
        
        x = box_data[d][0]
        y = box_data[d][1]        
        
        w = box_data[d][2]
        h = box_data[d][3]
       
        bottom = y + h
        right = x + w
        
        crop_dig = im[y:bottom, x:right]
       # print(crop_dig.shape)
        shape = crop_dig.shape
        if shape[0]*shape[1]==0 or w < .05*im.shape[0]: zoom_dig = ''
        else: zoom_dig = ndimage.interpolation.zoom(crop_dig, [32./shape[0], 32./shape[1]])
        name1 = n+'.png'        
        if zoom_dig != '' :
            misc.imsave(name1, zoom_dig)
        
        digits.append(name1)
    l = len(digits)    
   # if len(digits) < 5:
  #      digits.extend(['']*(5-l))
        
    return digits


def make_labels(boxes, image):
    
    dataset = np.ndarray(shape=(len(boxes[image]), image_size, image_size),
                                dtype=np.float32)                         
    #labels = np.ndarray(shape=(len(boxes[image])), dtype=np.int32)
    
    boxes = get_boxes(boxes, image)
    digits = get_image_digits(boxes, image)
   # print(len(digits))
    image_index = 0
    for i in range(len(digits)):
       # print (digits[i])
        try: 
                         
            image_data = (ndimage.imread(digits[i]).astype(float) - 
                        pixel_depth / 2) / pixel_depth
            if image_data.shape != (image_size, image_size):
                raise Exception('Unexpected image shape: %s' % str(image_data.shape))
            dataset[image_index, :, :] = image_data
            image_index +=1     
            print(image_index)      
        except IOError as e:
            print('Could not read:', digits[i], ':', e, '- it\'s ok, skipping.')
           # dataset[i, :,:] = 0
           # image_index +=1   
                
    num_images = image_index
    print(num_images)                    
    dataset = dataset[0:num_images, :, :]
    
    n = num_images/5
    r = num_images%5
    
    fig=plt.figure()   
    for i in range(n):
        for j in range(5):
            a=fig.add_subplot(n,5,i*5+j+1)
            plt.imshow(dataset[i*5+j, :, :])
        # a.set_title(chr(labels[indices[i]]+ord('A')))
            a.axes.get_xaxis().set_visible(False)
            a.axes.get_yaxis().set_visible(False)
    plt.show()
    
    if r > 0:
        showDataImages(dataset,num_images-r,r)
        
    okay = 0    
    while okay == 0 :
        i_labels = []
        for i in range(num_images):
            lab = (input('Enter a label for the image:'))               
            i_labels.append(lab)  
        okay = (input('Enter 1 for yes, 0 for no:'))  
          
   # print (i_labels)        
    labels = np.array(i_labels)   
  #  print(labels)    
    for f in os.listdir("./photos"):
        g = 'photos/' + f
        if g.endswith(".png"):os.remove(g)    
    labels = labels[0:num_images]          
    return dataset, labels        
   # showDataImages(dataset, 0, num_images)

def refine_data(pdata, plabels):
    data, labels = [], []
    zero = np.zeros(shape=(32, 32), dtype=np.float32)
    for i in range(plabels.shape[0]):
       # print(plabels.shape)
        if plabels[i]!=11:
            data.append(pdata[i])
            labels.append(plabels[i])
    
    if len(labels) < 5:
        data.extend([zero]*(5-len(labels)))
        labels.extend([11]*(5-len(labels)))
    return data, labels

def make_dataset(folder, boxes):
    dataset = np.ndarray(shape=(len(folder)*5, image_size, image_size),
                                dtype=np.float32)
    labels = np.ndarray(shape=(len(folder)*5), dtype=np.int32)
    for j, image in enumerate(folder):
        print(j,image)
        boxes = get_boxes(boxes, f+image)
        pdata, plabels = make_labels(boxes, f+image)
        data, lab = refine_data(pdata, plabels)
        for i in range(len(lab)):
            dataset[5*j+i,:,:] = data[i]
            labels[5*j+i] = lab[i]
            
    dataset = dataset[0:5*j, :, :]
    labels = labels[0:5*j]
    print('Full dataset tensor:', dataset.shape)
    print('Mean:', np.mean(dataset))
    print('Standard deviation:', np.std(dataset))
    print('Full labels tensor:', labels.shape)
    return dataset, labels

image_size = 32


num_labels = 12

def reformat(labels):
 
  # Map 2 to [0.0, 1.0, 0.0 ...], 3 to [0.0, 0.0, 1.0 ...], 11 to [0.0, 0.0, ...]
    labels = (np.arange(1, num_labels) == labels[:,None]).astype(np.float32)           
    return labels
              
labelstest_hot = reformat(labelstest)

In [4]:
image_size = 32
num_labels = 11

def reformat(dataset):
  dataset = dataset.reshape((-1, image_size * image_size)).astype(np.float32)
  # Map 2 to [0.0, 1.0, 0.0 ...], 3 to [0.0, 0.0, 1.0 ...]
 # labels = (np.arange(num_labels) == labels[:,None]).astype(np.float32)
  return dataset
train_digits = reformat(train_digits)
phototest = reformat(phototest)
print('Training set', train_digits.shape, train_digit_labels_hot.shape)

print('Test set', phototest.shape, labelstest_hot.shape)

Training set (167010, 1024) (167010, 11)
Test set (100, 1024) (100, 11)
In [5]:
def accuracy(predictions, labels):
  return (100.0 * np.sum(np.argmax(predictions, 1) == np.argmax(labels, 1))
          / predictions.shape[0])
def accuracy_seq(predictions, labels):
    a = 0
    s = predictions.shape[0]/5
    for i in range(s):
        a += ((np.sum(np.argmax(predictions[5*i:5*(i+1)], 1) == np.argmax(labels[5*i:5*(i+1)], 1)) >= 4.9))
    return 100.0 * a / s
In [6]:
# Network Parameters
n_hidden_1 = 1024 # 1st layer num features
n_hidden_2 = 512 # 2nd layer num features
n_input = 1024 # SVHN data input (img shape: 32*32)
n_classes = 11 # SVHN total classes (0-9 digits + blank)
batch_size = 40
test_batch = 100
p = 1e-5


graph = tf.Graph()
with graph.as_default():

    
    
    

    # tf Graph input
    tf_train_digits = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, shape=(batch_size, n_input))
    tf_train_digit_labels_hot = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, shape=(batch_size, n_classes))
    #tf_valid_dataset = tf.constant(valid_dataset)
    tf_phototest = tf.constant(phototest)
    
    # Create model
    def multilayer_perceptron(_X, _weights, _biases):
        layer_1 = tf.nn.relu(tf.add(tf.matmul(_X, _weights['h1']), _biases['b1'])) #Hidden layer with RELU activation
        layer_2 = tf.nn.relu(tf.add(tf.matmul(layer_1, _weights['h2']), _biases['b2'])) #Hidden layer with RELU activation
        return tf.matmul(layer_2, _weights['out']) + _biases['out']

    # Store layers weight & bias
    weights = {
        'h1': tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal([n_input, n_hidden_1], stddev = 0.05)),
        'h2': tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal([n_hidden_1, n_hidden_2], stddev = 0.05)),
        'out': tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal([n_hidden_2, n_classes], stddev = 0.05))
    }
    biases = {
        'b1': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([n_hidden_1])),
        'b2': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([n_hidden_2])),
        'out': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([n_classes]))
    }
    
    regularizer = np.multiply(p, tf.nn.l2_loss(weights['h1']))


    # Construct model
    pred = multilayer_perceptron(tf_train_digits, weights, biases)

    # Define loss and optimizer
    loss = tf.reduce_mean(tf.nn.softmax_cross_entropy_with_logits(pred, tf_train_digit_labels_hot)) + regularizer# Softmax loss
    global_step = tf.Variable(0)  # count the number of steps taken.
    learning_rate = tf.train.exponential_decay(0.4, global_step, 1000, 0.65, staircase=True)
    optimizer = tf.train.GradientDescentOptimizer(learning_rate).minimize(loss, global_step=global_step)

     # Predictions for the training, validation, and test data.
  
    train_prediction = tf.nn.softmax(pred)
    #valid_prediction = tf.nn.softmax(multilayer_perceptron (tf_valid_dataset, weights, biases))
    
    test_prediction = tf.nn.softmax(multilayer_perceptron(tf_phototest, weights, biases))
In [7]:
num_steps = 4001

with tf.Session(graph=graph) as session:
  tf.initialize_all_variables().run()
  print("Initialized")
  for step in range(num_steps):
    # Pick an offset within the training data, which has been randomized.
    # Note: we could use better randomization across epochs.
    offset = (step * batch_size) % (train_digit_labels_hot.shape[0])
    # Generate a minibatch.
    batch_data = train_digits[offset:(offset + batch_size), :]
    batch_labels = train_digit_labels_hot[offset:(offset + batch_size), :]
    # Prepare a dictionary telling the session where to feed the minibatch.
    # The key of the dictionary is the placeholder node of the graph to be fed,
    # and the value is the numpy array to feed to it.
    feed_dict = {tf_train_digits : batch_data, tf_train_digit_labels_hot : batch_labels}
    _, l, predictions = session.run(
      [optimizer, loss, train_prediction], feed_dict=feed_dict)
    if (step % 200 == 0):
      print("Minibatch loss at step %d: %f" % (step, l))
      print("Minibatch accuracy: %.1f%%" % accuracy(predictions, batch_labels))
  a = 0
  b = 0
  for i in range(10):
    offset = (step * test_batch) % (labelstest_hot.shape[0])
    test_data = phototest[offset:(offset + test_batch), :]
    test_labels = labelstest_hot[offset:(offset + test_batch), :]
    a += accuracy(test_prediction.eval(feed_dict={tf_phototest:test_data}), test_labels)
    b += accuracy_seq(test_prediction.eval(feed_dict={tf_phototest:test_data}), test_labels)
  a = a/10
  b = b/10
  print("Test accuracy: %.1f%%" % a)
  print("Test accuracy_seq: %.1f%%" % b)

Question 8¶

Is your model able to perform equally well on captured pictures or a live camera stream when compared to testing on the realistic dataset?

Answer: My model performed slightly better on the captured photos than on the realistic dataset. I did a fair amount of manipulation. First, I hand-cropped pictures which included buildings, cars, etc. so that only the numbers were present. Then I used OpenCV to find the contours in each picture and the corresponding bounding boxes. If less than two contours were present, I inverted the photo from black to white(see IMG_2745crop.JPG). From there I followed the methods of the realistic dataset, cutting photos along the bounding boxes. There were several differences. I did not include photos where the bounding box width was less than 5% of the full photo. I also added an interface where I looked at the photo and inputed a classification. I was surprised that the last two photos above were easily classified. For each set of contours from the original photo, I removed ones separating digits that were unclassifiable and added blanks so that every original photo was reduced to a sequence of five digits/blanks. The rest was the same as for the realistic dataset.

Step 4: Explore an Improvement for a Model¶

There are many things you can do once you have the basic classifier in place. One example would be to also localize where the numbers are on the image. The SVHN dataset provides bounding boxes that you can tune to train a localizer. Train a regression loss to the coordinates of the bounding box, and then test it.
